1
00:03:04,880 --> 00:03:09,351
Hello.
My name's Forrest. Forrest Gump.

2
00:03:15,040 --> 00:03:16,871
Do you want a chocolate?

3
00:03:19,200 --> 00:03:23,557
I could eat
about a million and a half of these.

4
00:03:23,640 --> 00:03:28,350
My mama always said
life was like a box of chocolates.

5
00:03:30,720 --> 00:03:34,030
You never know
what you're going to get.

6
00:03:40,320 --> 00:03:43,073
Those must be comfortable shoes.

7
00:03:43,160 --> 00:03:47,950
I bet you could walk all day in shoes
like that and not feel a thing.

8
00:03:50,440 --> 00:03:54,752
- I wish I had shoes like that.
- My feet hurt.

9
00:03:56,200 --> 00:03:58,589
Mama always said there's an awful lot

10
00:03:58,680 --> 00:04:01,831
you can tell about a person
by their shoes.

11
00:04:01,920 --> 00:04:05,196
Where they're going,
where they've been.

12
00:04:11,920 --> 00:04:14,514
I've worn lots of shoes.

13
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:18,675
I bet if I think about it real hard,

14
00:04:18,760 --> 00:04:22,275
I could remember
my first pair of shoes.

15
00:04:24,200 --> 00:04:26,998
Mama said they'd take me anywhere.

16
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:30,033
She said they was my magic shoes.

17
00:04:30,120 --> 00:04:33,510
All right, Forrest,
open your eyes now.

18
00:04:40,160 --> 00:04:42,196
Let's take a little walk around.

19
00:04:48,920 --> 00:04:50,831
How do those feel?

20
00:04:53,680 --> 00:04:58,117
His legs are strong, Mrs Gump,
as strong as I've ever seen.

21
00:04:58,200 --> 00:05:02,113
But his back's as
crooked as a politician.

22
00:05:02,200 --> 00:05:05,636
But we're going to straighten him
right up, aren't we, Forrest?

23
00:05:08,120 --> 00:05:12,159
When I was a baby, Mama named me
after the great Civil War hero

24
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:14,879
General Nathan Bedford Forrest.

25
00:05:14,960 --> 00:05:17,269
She said we was related to him
in some way.

26
00:05:17,360 --> 00:05:22,354
What he did was he started up
this club called the Ku Klux Klan.

27
00:05:22,440 --> 00:05:25,637
They'd all dress up
in their robes and their bed sheets

28
00:05:25,720 --> 00:05:30,077
and act like a bunch
of ghosts or spooks or something.

29
00:05:30,160 --> 00:05:33,869
They'd even put bed sheets
on their horses and ride around.

30
00:05:33,960 --> 00:05:37,953
And anyway, that's how
I got my name, Forrest Gump.

31
00:05:38,040 --> 00:05:41,749
Mama said the Forrest part
was to remind me that sometimes

32
00:05:41,840 --> 00:05:46,197
we all do things that, well,
just don't make no sense.

33
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:57,679
This way. Hold on.

34
00:05:58,040 --> 00:06:01,476
All right.
What are y'all staring at?

35
00:06:01,560 --> 00:06:05,838
Haven't you ever seen a little boy
with braces on his legs before?

36
00:06:07,040 --> 00:06:10,794
Don't ever let anybody tell you
they're better than you, Forrest.

37
00:06:10,880 --> 00:06:13,235
If God wanted everybody
to be the same,

38
00:06:13,320 --> 00:06:15,959
he'd have given us all
braces on our legs.

39
00:06:16,040 --> 00:06:19,316
Mama always had a way of explaining
things so I could understand them.

40
00:06:20,920 --> 00:06:24,435
We lived about
a quarter mile off Route 17,

41
00:06:24,520 --> 00:06:27,318
about a half mile
from the town of Greenbow, Alabama.

42
00:06:27,400 --> 00:06:30,198
That's in the county of Greenbow.

43
00:06:30,280 --> 00:06:34,558
Our house had been in Mama's family
since her grandpa's grandpa's grandpa

44
00:06:34,640 --> 00:06:37,712
had come across the ocean
about a thousand years ago.

45
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:42,237
Since it was just me and Mama
and we had all these empty rooms,

46
00:06:42,320 --> 00:06:46,472
Mama decided to let those rooms out,
mostly to people passing through,

47
00:06:46,560 --> 00:06:49,757
like from Mobile,
Montgomery, places like that.

48
00:06:49,840 --> 00:06:54,960
That's how me and Mama got money.
Mama was a real smart lady.

49
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:57,191
Remember what I told you, Forrest.

50
00:06:57,280 --> 00:07:00,477
You're no different
than anybody else is.

51
00:07:02,240 --> 00:07:06,995
Did you hear what I said, Forrest?
You're the same as everybody else.

52
00:07:07,080 --> 00:07:09,389
You are no different.

53
00:07:09,480 --> 00:07:15,749
Your boy's different, Mrs Gump.
His I.Q. Is 75.

54
00:07:15,840 --> 00:07:19,594
Well, we're all different,
Mr Hancock.

55
00:07:22,760 --> 00:07:25,558
She wanted me to have
the finest education,

56
00:07:25,640 --> 00:07:29,076
so she took me to
the Greenbow County Central School.

57
00:07:29,160 --> 00:07:31,230
I met the principal and all.

58
00:07:31,320 --> 00:07:34,517
I want to show you
something, Mrs Gump.

59
00:07:34,600 --> 00:07:41,039
Now, this is normal.
Forrest is right here.

60
00:07:41,840 --> 00:07:46,277
The state requires a minimum I.Q.
Of 80 to attend public school.

61
00:07:46,360 --> 00:07:50,433
Mrs Gump, he's going to have
to go to a special school.

62
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:55,116
- He'll be just fine.
- What does normal mean anyway?

63
00:07:55,200 --> 00:08:00,228
He might be a bit on the slow side,
but my boy Forrest

64
00:08:00,320 --> 00:08:03,392
will get the same opportunities
as everyone else.

65
00:08:03,480 --> 00:08:07,598
He's not going to some special school
to learn how to retread tyres.

66
00:08:07,680 --> 00:08:11,036
We're talking about
five little points here.

67
00:08:12,280 --> 00:08:15,078
There must be something can be done.

68
00:08:16,520 --> 00:08:19,193
We're a progressive school system.

69
00:08:19,600 --> 00:08:22,592
We don't want to see
anybody left behind.

70
00:08:22,680 --> 00:08:27,196
Is there a Mr Gump, Mrs Gump?

71
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:31,796
He's on vacation.

72
00:08:47,760 --> 00:08:51,992
Your mama sure does care
about your schooling, son.

73
00:08:56,960 --> 00:08:59,428
You don't say much, do you?

74
00:09:10,720 --> 00:09:15,316
"Finally, he had to try.
It looked easy, but...

75
00:09:15,400 --> 00:09:17,789
"Oh, what happened. First they..."

76
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:22,237
- Mama, what's vacation mean?
- Vacation?

77
00:09:22,320 --> 00:09:24,993
Where daddy went?

78
00:09:26,640 --> 00:09:32,431
Vacation's when you go somewhere...
and you don't ever come back.

79
00:09:36,880 --> 00:09:41,351
Anyway, I guess you could say
me and Mama was on our own.

80
00:09:41,480 --> 00:09:45,632
But we didn't mind.
Our house was never empty.

81
00:09:45,720 --> 00:09:48,518
There was always
folks coming and going.

82
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:53,071
- Supper! It's supper, everyone!
- That sure looks special.

83
00:09:53,160 --> 00:09:55,549
Sometimes, we had so many people
staying with us

84
00:09:55,640 --> 00:09:58,837
that every room was filled,
with travellers, you know,

85
00:09:58,920 --> 00:10:04,597
folks living out of their suitcases
and hat cases and sample cases.

86
00:10:04,680 --> 00:10:08,593
Forrest Gump,
it's suppertime! Forrest?

87
00:10:08,680 --> 00:10:13,913
One time, a young man was staying
with us, and he had a guitar case.

88
00:10:27,480 --> 00:10:31,268
Forrest, I told you not to bother
this nice young man.

89
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:32,839
No, that's all right, ma'am.

90
00:10:32,920 --> 00:10:36,196
I was showing him
a thing or two on the guitar.

91
00:10:36,280 --> 00:10:39,078
All right. Supper's ready
if y'all want to eat.

92
00:10:39,160 --> 00:10:41,958
Yeah, that sounds good.
Thank you, ma'am.

93
00:10:42,040 --> 00:10:47,273
Say, show me that crazy little walk
you did there. Slow it down some.

94
00:10:49,200 --> 00:10:53,239
I liked that guitar. It sounded good.

95
00:10:54,440 --> 00:11:00,913
I started moving around to the music,
swinging my hips.

96
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:06,549
This one night,
me and Mama was out shopping,

97
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:09,791
and we walked by Benson's furniture
and appliance store, and guess what?

98
00:11:22,560 --> 00:11:25,313
This is not for children's eyes.

99
00:11:27,560 --> 00:11:31,678
Some years later, that handsome
young man who they called The King,

100
00:11:31,760 --> 00:11:34,513
well, he sung too many songs.

101
00:11:34,600 --> 00:11:37,478
Had himself a heart attack
or something.

102
00:11:37,560 --> 00:11:40,393
It must be hard being a king.

103
00:11:43,800 --> 00:11:46,360
It's funny how you remember some
things, but some things you can't.

104
00:11:47,960 --> 00:11:52,750
- You do your very best now, Forrest.
- I sure will, Mama.

105
00:11:52,840 --> 00:11:57,595
I remember the bus ride
on the first day of school very well.

106
00:12:00,520 --> 00:12:02,351
Are you coming along?

107
00:12:02,440 --> 00:12:05,750
Mama said not to take rides
from strangers.

108
00:12:05,840 --> 00:12:07,751
This is the bus to school.

109
00:12:10,640 --> 00:12:15,589
- I'm Forrest, Forrest Gump.
- I'm Dorothy Harris.

110
00:12:15,680 --> 00:12:17,830
Well, now we ain't strangers anymore.

111
00:12:30,400 --> 00:12:32,789
This seat's taken.

112
00:12:34,320 --> 00:12:36,151
It's taken.

113
00:12:43,280 --> 00:12:45,111
You can't sit here.

114
00:12:47,480 --> 00:12:50,677
You know, it's funny what
a young man recollects,

115
00:12:50,760 --> 00:12:53,433
'cause I don't remember being born.

116
00:12:53,520 --> 00:12:56,478
I don't recall what I got
for my first Christmas,

117
00:12:56,560 --> 00:13:00,109
and I don't know when I went
on my first outdoor picnic,

118
00:13:00,200 --> 00:13:03,988
but I do remember
the first time I heard

119
00:13:04,080 --> 00:13:07,436
the sweetest voice in the wide world.

120
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:10,353
You can sit here if you want.

121
00:13:12,440 --> 00:13:16,638
I had never seen anything
so beautiful in my life.

122
00:13:16,760 --> 00:13:18,796
She was like an angel.

123
00:13:18,880 --> 00:13:22,111
Well, are you going
to sit down or aren't you?

124
00:13:26,440 --> 00:13:28,351
What's wrong with your legs?

125
00:13:28,440 --> 00:13:33,070
Nothing at all, thank you.
My legs are just fine and dandy.

126
00:13:33,160 --> 00:13:35,958
I just sat next to her on that bus

127
00:13:36,040 --> 00:13:38,793
and had a conversation
all the way to school.

128
00:13:38,880 --> 00:13:41,110
My back's crooked
like a question mark.

129
00:13:41,200 --> 00:13:46,069
Next to Mama, no one ever talked
to me or asked me questions.

130
00:13:46,160 --> 00:13:48,390
Are you stupid or something?

131
00:13:48,480 --> 00:13:51,870
Mama says,
"Stupid is as stupid does."

132
00:13:51,960 --> 00:13:56,829
- I'm Jenny.
- I'm Forrest, Forrest Gump.

133
00:13:56,920 --> 00:13:59,559
From that day on,
we was always together.

134
00:13:59,640 --> 00:14:02,234
Jenny and me
was like peas and carrots.

135
00:14:04,800 --> 00:14:07,030
She taught me how to climb.

136
00:14:07,120 --> 00:14:09,429
Come on, Forrest, you can do it.

137
00:14:09,520 --> 00:14:11,988
I showed her how to dangle.

138
00:14:13,720 --> 00:14:18,874
She helped me learn how to read,
and I showed her how to swing.

139
00:14:20,200 --> 00:14:24,751
Sometimes, we'd just sit out
and wait for the stars.

140
00:14:24,840 --> 00:14:29,960
- Mama's going to worry about me.
- Just stay a little longer.

141
00:14:30,040 --> 00:14:33,953
For some reason,
Jenny never wanted to go home.

142
00:14:34,040 --> 00:14:36,634
OK, Jenny, I'll stay.

143
00:14:36,720 --> 00:14:40,030
She was my most special friend.

144
00:14:43,080 --> 00:14:45,640
My only friend.

145
00:14:47,320 --> 00:14:51,029
My Mama always told me
that miracles happen every day.

146
00:14:51,120 --> 00:14:54,669
Some people don't think so,
but they do.

147
00:14:56,800 --> 00:14:59,678
Hey, dummy!

148
00:14:59,880 --> 00:15:02,155
Are you retarded,
or just plain stupid?

149
00:15:02,240 --> 00:15:05,391
- Look, I'm Forrest Gimp.
- Just run away, Forrest.

150
00:15:06,720 --> 00:15:09,553
Run, Forrest! Run away! Hurry!

151
00:15:09,800 --> 00:15:12,997
- Get the bikes!
- Let's get him! Come on!

152
00:15:13,080 --> 00:15:17,631
Look out, dummy!
We're going to get you!

153
00:15:17,720 --> 00:15:21,793
Run, Forrest, run! Run, Forrest!

154
00:15:23,160 --> 00:15:25,435
Come back here, you!

155
00:15:38,320 --> 00:15:41,995
Run, Forrest! Run!

156
00:16:11,400 --> 00:16:14,915
You wouldn't
believe it if I told you,

157
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:18,231
but I can run like the wind blows.

158
00:16:21,360 --> 00:16:27,117
From that day on, if I was
going somewhere, I was running.

159
00:16:58,560 --> 00:17:01,677
That boy sure is a running fool.

160
00:17:05,360 --> 00:17:09,194
Remember how I told you that Jenny
never seemed to want to go home?

161
00:17:09,280 --> 00:17:12,670
She lived in a house
that was as old as Alabama.

162
00:17:12,760 --> 00:17:15,194
Her mama had gone to heaven
when she was five,

163
00:17:15,280 --> 00:17:19,637
and her daddy was
some kind of a farmer.

164
00:17:19,720 --> 00:17:21,517
Jenny?

165
00:17:21,600 --> 00:17:23,556
He was a very loving man.

166
00:17:23,640 --> 00:17:27,758
He was always kissing
and touching her and her sisters.

167
00:17:29,400 --> 00:17:34,155
And then this one time, Jenny
wasn't on the bus to go to school.

168
00:17:34,240 --> 00:17:36,629
Jenny,
why didn't you come to school today?

169
00:17:37,560 --> 00:17:39,391
Daddy's taking a nap.

170
00:17:40,800 --> 00:17:42,392
Come on!

171
00:17:43,120 --> 00:17:48,478
Jenny, where'd you run to?
You better get back here, girl!

172
00:17:49,960 --> 00:17:52,269
Where you at?

173
00:17:54,960 --> 00:17:58,270
Jenny! Jenny, where you at?

174
00:18:01,880 --> 00:18:05,031
Pray with me, Forrest. Pray with me.

175
00:18:06,480 --> 00:18:11,508
Dear God, make me a bird so I can fly
far, far, far away from here.

176
00:18:11,600 --> 00:18:16,310
Dear God, make me a bird
so I can fly far...

177
00:18:16,400 --> 00:18:19,153
Mama always said God is mysterious.

178
00:18:20,800 --> 00:18:23,234
He didn't turn Jenny
into a bird that day.

179
00:18:23,320 --> 00:18:26,915
Instead, he had the police say

180
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:30,390
Jenny didn't have to stay
in that house no more.

181
00:18:30,480 --> 00:18:34,598
She was to live with her grandma,
just over on Creekmore Avenue,

182
00:18:34,680 --> 00:18:38,514
which made me happy,
'cause she was so close.

183
00:18:39,880 --> 00:18:45,159
Some nights, Jenny'd sneak out
and come on over to my house,

184
00:18:45,240 --> 00:18:50,678
just 'cause she said she was scared.
Scared of what, I don't know.

185
00:18:50,760 --> 00:18:56,073
But I think it was her grandma's dog.
He was a mean dog.

186
00:18:56,400 --> 00:19:00,552
Anyway, Jenny and me was best friends
all the way up through high school.

187
00:19:02,800 --> 00:19:05,075
- Hey, stupid!
- Quit it!

188
00:19:05,160 --> 00:19:06,513
Run, Forrest, run!

189
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:11,037
- Didn't you hear me, stupid?
- Run, Forrest!

190
00:19:11,120 --> 00:19:15,511
Get in the truck!
Come on! He's getting away! Move it!

191
00:19:15,600 --> 00:19:17,909
Run, Forrest! Run!

192
00:19:44,520 --> 00:19:46,875
Run, Forrest!

193
00:19:48,960 --> 00:19:53,192
Now, it used to be
I ran to get where I was going.

194
00:19:53,280 --> 00:19:56,590
I never thought
it would take me anywhere.

195
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:25,991
Who in the hell is that?

196
00:20:26,080 --> 00:20:30,710
That is Forrest Gump, coach.
Just a local idiot.

197
00:20:30,840 --> 00:20:35,868
And can you believe it?
I got to go to college, too.

198
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:44,676
- Forrest, move it! Run!
- OK!

199
00:20:44,760 --> 00:20:48,514
- Run!
- Run, you stupid son of a bitch!

200
00:21:00,840 --> 00:21:03,593
Run, son of a bitch, run! Go! Run!

201
00:21:19,240 --> 00:21:24,268
He must be the stupidest son of
a bitch alive, but he sure is fast.

202
00:21:27,200 --> 00:21:32,069
Now, maybe it's just me,
but college was very confusing times.

203
00:21:33,440 --> 00:21:35,635
Federal troops,
enforcing a court order,

204
00:21:35,720 --> 00:21:37,870
integrated
the University of Alabama today.

205
00:21:37,960 --> 00:21:39,393
Two Negroes were admitted,

206
00:21:39,480 --> 00:21:42,313
but only after Governor George
Wallace had carried out

207
00:21:42,400 --> 00:21:45,551
his symbolic threat
to stand in the schoolhouse door.

208
00:21:48,280 --> 00:21:50,157
Earl, what's going on?

209
00:21:50,240 --> 00:21:52,629
Coons are trying to get into school.

210
00:21:52,720 --> 00:21:55,518
Coons? When racoons
tried getting on our back porch,

211
00:21:55,600 --> 00:21:57,830
Mama just chased them off
with a broom.

212
00:21:57,920 --> 00:22:02,596
Not racoons, you idiot. Niggers.
They want to go to school with us.

213
00:22:02,680 --> 00:22:04,557
With us? They do?

214
00:22:04,640 --> 00:22:06,471
Shortly after Governor Wallace

215
00:22:06,560 --> 00:22:09,313
had carried out his promise
to block the doorway,

216
00:22:09,400 --> 00:22:11,516
President Kennedy
ordered the Secretary of Defence

217
00:22:11,600 --> 00:22:13,477
to use military force.

218
00:22:13,560 --> 00:22:16,120
Here, by videotape,
is the encounter by General Graham,

219
00:22:16,200 --> 00:22:18,714
commander of the national guard,
and Governor Wallace.

220
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:22,839
Because these national guardsmen
are here today

221
00:22:22,920 --> 00:22:26,549
as federal soldiers for Alabama,
and they live within our borders.

222
00:22:26,640 --> 00:22:30,952
They are our brothers.
We are winning in this fight,

223
00:22:31,040 --> 00:22:35,318
because we are awakening
the American people to the dangers

224
00:22:35,400 --> 00:22:39,916
that we have spoken about
so many times, so evident today,

225
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:43,515
a trend toward military
dictatorship in this country.

226
00:22:46,360 --> 00:22:47,952
And so, at day's end,

227
00:22:48,040 --> 00:22:51,715
the University of Alabama
in Tuscaloosa had been desegregated,

228
00:22:51,800 --> 00:22:54,872
and students Jimmy Hood
and Vivian Malone

229
00:22:54,960 --> 00:22:58,032
had been signed up
for summer classes.

230
00:22:59,720 --> 00:23:02,996
Ma'am, you dropped your book. Ma'am.

231
00:23:03,880 --> 00:23:05,518
Governor Wallace
did what he promised.

232
00:23:05,600 --> 00:23:08,910
By being on the Tuscaloosa campus,
he kept the mob from gathering...

233
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:12,436
- Say, wasn't that Gump?
- Naw, that couldn't be.

234
00:23:12,520 --> 00:23:15,318
It sure as hell was.

235
00:23:18,480 --> 00:23:22,792
A few years later, that angry
little man at the schoolhouse door

236
00:23:22,880 --> 00:23:25,838
thought it'd be a good idea
and ran for President.

